{{Infobox person | name = Iben Browning | image = Iben Browning.jpg | image_size = 167px | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1918|01|18}} | birth_place = [[Edna, Texas]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1991|07|18|1918|01|18}} | death_place = [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]] | nationality = United States | other_names = | occupation = business consultant | known_for = erroneous earthquake prediction }}
'''Iben Browning''' (January 9, 1918 &ndash; July 18, 1991) was an American business consultant, author, and "self-proclaimed [[climatologist]]."<ref name="Farley">{{cite book|last1=Farley|first1=John E.|title=Earthquake Fears, Predictions, and Preparations in Mid-America|publisher=Southern Illinois University Press}}</ref>{{rp|p. 2}} He is most notable for having made various failed predictions of [[disaster]]s involving [[climate]], [[volcano]]es, [[earthquake]]s, and government collapse.<ref name="USGS"/>{{rp|p. 11}}
==Life and career== Browning was born in [[Edna, Texas]], grew up in [[Jackson County, Texas]], and graduated from [[Southwest Texas State Teachers College]] in 1937, majoring in both math and physics. During World War II, he served in the [[U.S. Army Air Corps]]. Subsequently, he earned an M.A. at the [[University of Texas at Austin]] in 1947, and then his doctorate (Ph.D.) the following year at the same school. His doctorate was in zoology, with minors in genetics and bacteriology.
Browning worked in various scientific fields, including artificial intelligence and bio-engineering, and eventually became interested in long-term weather forecasting and climate changes.<ref name="nyt" /> He believed that climate fluctuations are caused by changes in the amount of particulate matter in the atmosphere mostly from volcanic activity. He believed that volcanic activity can be triggered by land tidal forces caused by the Moon, Earth's elliptical orbit of the Sun, and the alignment of these three bodies. His climate predictions assumed that the dust thrown into the atmosphere by those eruptions reflects sunlight, which results in climatic cooling. Browning believed that climatic changes, especially cooling, are associated with increased troubles in human society, including famine, revolutions, and war.<ref>Winkless, Nels III and Browning, Iben. ''Climate and the Affairs of Men'', Fraser Publishing, 1975. {{ISBN|0061295507}}</ref>
After founding ''The Browning Newsletter'' in 1974,<ref>[https://browningclimate.com/about/ https://browningclimate.com/about/]</ref> Browning described his climatic theories and findings in ''Climate and the Affairs of Men'' (1975), which he co-authored with Nels Winkless III. At that time, he believed that Earth had been through a long warm period and was moving into a dangerous cooling phase. He also declared that he had not detected any effect of human activity on the climate.
Browning received notoriety for his erroneous [[earthquake prediction#Browning|prediction]] that a major [[earthquake]] would occur on the [[New Madrid Fault]] around December 2 and 3, 1990. This prediction had no scientific legitimacy,<ref name="Farley"/>{{rp|p. 3}} and was largely ignored by credentialed seismologists, who thought it would give the prediction undeserved attention if they had debunked it in public.<ref name="USGS"/>{{rp|p. 21}} In spite of this it was widely reported in the national media, which promoted fear, anxiety, and hysteria<ref name="USGS"/>{{rp|p. 3}} among residents of the Mississippi Valley. No earthquake occurred in that area on those dates. A study done by the USGS to understand the causes of the earthquake scare described Browning's methodology as [[pseudoscience]].<ref name="USGS">{{citation |last1= Spence |first1= William |last2= Herrmann |first2= Robert B. |last3= Johnston |first3= Arch C. |last4= Reagor |first4= Glen |lastauthoramp=yes |year= 1993 |title= Responses to Iben Browning's Prediction of a 1990 New Madrid, Missouri, Earthquake |journal= U.S. Geological Survey |volume= Circular 1083 |url= http://pubs.usgs.gov/circ/1993/1083/report.pdf }}. </ref>
Browning wrote four books, held 90 patents, and served as a [[climatologist]] and business consultant to [[Paine Webber]] in various scientific and engineering fields. He was married to the former Florence Pinto and had one daughter, Evelyn Browning-Garriss.,<ref>[https://www.desmogblog.com/evelyn-browning-garriss https://www.desmogblog.com/evelyn-browning-garriss]</ref> who succeeded him as editor of 'The Browning Newsletter'. He lived his later years in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]] and died at his home there on July 18, 1991 from a heart attack at the age of 73.<ref name="nyt">[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE5DA1F38F933A15754C0A967958260 obituary], ''[[New York Times]]'', July 20, 1991</ref><ref>Social Security Death Index</ref><ref>U.S. World War II Army Enlistment Records</ref>
