The '''Institute of Aviation''' or '''Warsaw Institute of Aviation''' (Polish ''Instytut Lotnictwa'') is a research and development center established in 1926, located in [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]].
==External links== * [http://www.ilot.edu.pl Official website of the Institute of Aviation] * [http://www.cntpolska.pl Official website of the New Technologies Center (NTC)] * [http://www.edcpolska.pl Official website of the Engineering Design Center (EDC)] * [http://www.cbmk.pl Official website of the Materials and Structures Research Centre (MSRC)] * [http://www.netinstytut.edu.pl Official website of the Net Institute (NET)] * [http://www.erainzyniera.pl Official website of The Age of Engineers]
{{DEFAULTSORT:Institute Of Aviation, Warsaw}} [[Category:Aviation organisations based in Poland]] [[Category:Electrical engineering companies]] [[Category:Organizations established in 1926]] [[Category:Science and technology in Poland|aviation]] [[Category:Science education]] [[Category:Aviation research institutes]] {{aviation-stub}} {{Poland-stub}}

The '''J-phenomenon''' was a hypothetical form of [[X-ray]] behaviour similar to [[X-ray fluorescence]].  It was reported and studied by [[Charles Glover Barkla|C. G. Barkla]] but other scientists were not persuaded that that this was a different mechanism from other known effects such as [[Compton scattering]] and so the theory was not successful.<ref name=BW/><ref name=MM/>

